/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. /ITShir Hakavod/XX, attributed to the Ashkenazi pietist Judah the
H/±asid of Regensburg (1150-1217), is simultaneously our traditionÚs most
unabashedly anthropomorphic depiction of God and its most eloquent ref-
utation of a purely anthropomorphic conception of divinity. All imagery
is relative, declares the poet, for it reflects only the preconceptions and
momentary passions of the tradition and the era--and yet our total fund
of imagery is precious and something to celebrate because it is ultimately
the only way we mortals have to honor and glorify God. So this song is
as much a poem about the tradition as it is about God. It makes use of
many key words in the Bible and the rabbinic tradition that express the
power and beauty of the divine, including: /ITKavod/XX (glory, honor),
/ITTifarah / Tiferet/XX (splendor, beauty), /ITEmet/XX (truth), /ITTzedek/XX (justice), /ITPeÚer/XX
(glory, beauty), /ITKodesh/XX (Holiness), /ITGedulah/XX (greatness), /ITGevurah/XX (power),
/ITMeluh/±ah/XX (majesty, rule), /ITAtarah / Ateret/XX (crown), /ITDodim/XX (friendship, love)-
--words that, because of their elusiveness and untranslatability, end up car-
rying us beyond imagery and beyond conventional notions of beauty.    /SC/XXJ.R./XX/PR
/PR
/PR
/PR
/PG454/XX/PR
So aged when you sit as judge; but youthful when you/PR
fight,/PR
a warrior, with many hands, and terrors to give fright./PR
HereÚs armor of your helmet, invincibility,/PR
your outstretched arm and mighty hand insure your/PR
victory./PR
/PR
The sparkling dewdrops, a head of shimmering light,/PR
your locks a darkest ebony from moisture of the night./PR
You call me your reknown, for you desire me well,/PR
as you appear before me with the splendor of gazelle./PR
/PR
Crowned by the purest gold (let imagery allow),/PR
engraven there, your holy name, inscribed upon your brow./PR
LoveÚs graciousness and honor adorn your radiance,/PR
your people are a crown to you and your magnificence./PR
/PR
Magnificent your plaited locks, a youthful head/PR
unfurled,/PR
so absolute the blackness of your hair in ringlets curled./PR
Now justiceÚs abode is here, the splendor of your shrine,/PR
its eminence the summit of your happiness sublime./PR
/PR
So treasured is the crown that rests within your hand,/PR
a diadem of sovereignty, a splendid royal band./PR
On you it is now borne, and with it you adorn/PR
your people, now made precious with the beauty you have/PR
worn./PI/PR
